anch is especially bad in GitButler’s multi-branch workflow.\n\nBut I would update the plan/docs to explicitly say the future association model is many-to-many:\n\n```text\nproject session object:\n  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n\nrelationship key on future explicit targets:\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nAnd maybe later, if we need richer provenance:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"session_key\": \"S\",\n  \"target\": \"branch:feature/checkout-currency\",\n  \"kind\": \"contributed-code\",\n  \"commit_ids\": [\"...\"],\n  \"created_at\": \"...\"\n}\n```\n\nBut not now. The small correct move is: keep session data project-scoped, and design future target links as references, not ownership.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:25:17.684Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}